From: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Date: 2026-05-13
Subject: [PATCH] ps4_mts: v103 — AN restart from ndo_open to provoke MAC link latch

After 100+ live BAR-poke tests + 8 agent rounds, three independent
agents (hermes/kimi/deepseek) converged on the same diagnosis:

The MAC's BAR+0x04 bit 0 (link-up status) is a ONE-SHOT, edge-triggered
latch fired on internal PCS/RGMII synchronization to a "link up" state.
The bit 9 of BAR+0x06c ("TX DMA ready") is read-only HW status, set
when MAC bit 0 latches.  Without bit 9, TX engine refuses to fetch
descriptors despite correct format, valid doorbell.

In v91 boot (no netdev, no RX prefill), kthread's first AN restart
fired at t~=5s and the PHY/MAC link transition that followed was the
latch event → bit 0 set → bit 9 gated open → TX would have worked.

In v97+ boots, the same kthread AN restart fires, but ndo_open's engine
reset + RX-ring pre-fill happen *after* the latch window already
expired.  MAC decided "no link" permanently.  RX continues to work
because RX path doesn't require MAC bit 0 (just buf_lo + OWN handling).
TX requires bit 9 of 0x06c which requires MAC bit 0 which requires a
fresh link-up edge that MAC can no longer see.

v103 fix: from ndo_open (post engine reset + ring re-init + carrier
checks), replay Orbis's gbe:phy_ctrl event-1 recovery sequence to
trigger a fresh PHY auto-negotiation cycle:
  - reg9 |= 0x0200 (1000BT advertise re-asserted)
  - reg4 |= 0x0180 (ANAR pause + 100full re-asserted)
  - BMCR |= 0x1200 (AN enable + restart)
The new base page goes out, partner ACKs, MAC sees a fresh link
transition, fires bit 2 LINK_CHANGE IRQ, latches bit 0 of 0x04, gates
open bit 9 of 0x06c.  TX engine then starts fetching descriptors that
have been stranded for 47+ xmits.

Verified live (no reboot): bit 9 of 0x06c is HW-status only,
untouchable by direct writes; only path to set it is via MAC's
natural link-up edge.

Sources:
  - checkpoint/docs/research/hermes-v102-trigger-link-change-irq.md
  - checkpoint/docs/research/kimi-v102-link-latch-timing.md
  - checkpoint/docs/research/deepseek-v102-bit3-irq-meaning.md

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>
Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -1384,6 +1384,55 @@
 	 * unconditionally clearing it here races with the kthread cache. */
 	if (readl(mts->bar + MTS_LINK_STATUS) & 0x1)
 		netif_carrier_on(ndev);
+
+	/* v103: trigger fresh PHY auto-negotiation from ndo_open AFTER
+	 * engines are running and RX descriptors are fully primed.
+	 *
+	 * Rationale (hermes/kimi/deepseek convergent finding, 2026-05-13):
+	 * MAC's BAR+0x04 bit 0 link-up latch is a ONE-SHOT, edge-triggered
+	 * on internal PCS/RGMII link tuple transition (0 → up).  In v91
+	 * boot (no netdev), kthread's first AN restart fired AT t~=5s, MAC
+	 * saw the resulting PHY link transition, and bit 0 latched
+	 * (linkreg=0xb19).  In v97+ boots, kthread fires same AN restart
+	 * BUT the latch window is then disturbed by ndo_open's engine
+	 * reset and RX ring pre-fill — by the time ndo_open completes
+	 * with real descriptors, the one-shot window has expired and MAC
+	 * has decided "no link" permanently.  No subsequent PHY/MAC event
+	 * gets bit 0 to latch.
+	 *
+	 * Without bit 0 latched, BAR+0x06c bit 9 (HW-driven "TX DMA
+	 * ready" status) stays 0 — the TX engine refuses to fetch
+	 * descriptors despite correct format, valid kick.  Result: TX
+	 * dropped 100% with descriptors stranded in DMA memory.
+	 *
+	 * Replicate the Orbis gbe:phy_ctrl event-1 recovery sequence:
+	 *  - reg9 (1000BT_CTRL) |= 0x0200 (re-advertise 1000T half)
+	 *  - reg4 (ANAR) |= 0x0180 (assert pause + 100full)
+	 *  - BMCR (reg0) |= 0x1200 (AN enable + restart)
+	 * which generates a fresh PHY base page → partner ACKs → MAC's
+	 * internal link state machine sees a new transition → bit 2
+	 * LINK_CHANGE IRQ fires → bit 0 of 0x04 latches → bit 9 of 0x06c
+	 * gates open → TX engine fetches descriptors.
+	 *
+	 * Verified live (2026-05-13): bit 9 of 0x06c is HW-status only,
+	 * untouchable by direct writes.  Only path to set it is via the
+	 * MAC's natural link-up event.
+	 */
+	{
+		u16 v16;
+
+		if (mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x09, &v16) == 0)
+			mts_smi_c22_write(mts, 0x09, v16 | 0x0200);
+		if (mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x04, &v16) == 0)
+			mts_smi_c22_write(mts, 0x04, v16 | 0x0180);
+		if (mts_smi_c22_read(mts, 0x00, &v16) == 0) {
+			mts_smi_c22_write(mts, 0x00, v16 | 0x1200);
+			dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+				 "v103: ndo_open AN restart BMCR 0x%04x -> 0x%04x (provoke fresh link-change for MAC bit 0 latch)\n",
+				 v16, v16 | 0x1200);
+		}
+	}
+
 	return 0;
 }
 
